## U.S. Federal Statutes on the Census

This article is, regrettably, part of [a series](/Category:United_States) on the grand edifice known as the [United States Code](/United_States_Code). Consider it a guided tour through the legislative labyrinth, where every turn leads to another meticulously cataloged statute.

### The Architect's Blueprint: Navigating the [United States Code](/United_States_Code)

The [United States Code](/United_States_Code) serves as the official compilation and codification of the general and permanent federal laws of the [United States](/United_States). It’s a vast, sprawling collection, organized into distinct titles, each dedicated to a broad subject area. Imagine it as a library, but instead of compelling narratives, it contains the definitive legal framework that governs everything from the mundane to the utterly obscure.

For those who enjoy the morbid fascination of legislative categorization, here's a comprehensive, and frankly exhaustive, list of these foundational titles:

*   [Title 1](/Title_1_of_the_United_States_Code) - General Provisions: The foundational rules, the preamble to the bureaucratic epic.
*   [Title 2](/Title_2_of_the_United_States_Code) - The Congress: Where the magic, or at least the legislation, happens.
*   [Title 3](/Title_3_of_the_United_States_Code) - The President: The executive branch's playbook.
